<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">32732454</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2021</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>30</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2022</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>07</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1543-2742</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>30</Volume><Issue>5</Issue><PubDate><Year>2020</Year><Month>Sep</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sport nutrition and exercise metabolism</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sport Nutr Exerc Metab</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>High Prevalence of Cannabidiol Use Within Male Professional Rugby Union and League Players: A Quest for Pain Relief and Enhanced Recovery.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>315</StartPage><EndPage>322</EndPage><MedlinePgn>315-322</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/ijsnem.2020-0151</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">ijsnem.2020-0151</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Rugby is characterized by frequent high-intensity collisions, resulting in muscle soreness. Players consequently seek strategies to reduce soreness and accelerate recovery, with an emerging method being cannabidiol (CBD), despite anti-doping risks. The prevalence and rationale for CBD use in rugby has not been explored; therefore, we recruited professional male players to complete a survey on CBD. Goodness of fit chi-square (&#x3c7;2) was used to assess CBD use between codes and player position. Effects of age on use were determined using &#x3c7;2 tests of independence. Twenty-five teams provided 517 player responses. While the majority of players had never used CBD (p &lt; .001, V = 0.24), 26% had either used it (18%) or were still using it (8%). Significantly more CBD use was observed in rugby union compared with rugby league (p = .004, V = 0.13), but player position was not a factor (p = .760, V = 0.013). CBD use increased with players' age (p &lt; .001, V = 0.28), with mean use reaching 41% in the players aged 28 years and older category (p &lt; .0001). The players using CBD primarily used the Internet (73%) or another teammate (61%) to obtain information, with only 16% consulting a nutritionist. The main reasons for CBD use were improving recovery/pain (80%) and sleep (78%), with 68% of players reporting a perceived benefit. These data highlight the need for immediate education on the risks of CBD, as well as the need to explore the claims regarding pain and sleep.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kasper</LastName><ForeName>Andreas M</ForeName><Initials>AM</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Liverpool John Moores University.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sparks</LastName><ForeName>S Andy</ForeName><Initials>SA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Edge Hill University.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hooks</LastName><ForeName>Matthew</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Liverpool John Moores University.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Skeer</LastName><ForeName>Matthew</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Liverpool John Moores University.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Webb</LastName><ForeName>Benjamin</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Liverpool John Moores University.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Nia</LastName><ForeName>Houman</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Liverpool John Moores University.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Morton</LastName><ForeName>James P</ForeName><Initials>JP</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Liverpool John Moores Unive